Britain anticipates an imminent statement from the IRA regarding a potential end to violence, following a plea from its political wing.
The Good Friday peace deal of 1998 brought relative calm to Northern Ireland, but concerns remain about ongoing criminal activities by paramilitary groups.
Meetings between political leaders aim to maintain dialogue and address tensions during the Protestant marching season.
Calls for the IRA to fully embrace democracy have been made, with hopes that a positive response will propel the peace process forward.
The key lies in the IRA's commitment to disarm and cease all threatening actions, paving the way for lasting cooperation between Catholics and Protestants.
